{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657505/1924032301/0074.xml":{"full_text":"DAWES PLAN IS FACING\nSNIPING OF POLITICIANS\nDangers Beset Any Reparations Settle\nment by Virtue of Europe\u2019s Prone\nness to Procrastinate.\nrtt OLIVER OWEX KUHN.\nWHEN* Gen. Charles G. Dawes\napproached the general\nreparations problem in\nEurope, with the view of\nreaching- a solution aaid making pos\nsible restoration of the economic.\nJinancial and commercial life of the\ncontinent he did so with a positive\naltitude, but. nevertheless, he kept\nhis fingers crossed behind him.\nGen. Dawes knew, as all acquainted\nwith the varying tides of European\npolitics know, it matters little how\nfour-square any proposal may be,\nhow absolutely vital it may be to the\nlife and iwogress of peoples' gener\nally. it first must be shaped to the\nideas and nationalistic political de\nsires of statesmen who may be in\ni\u00bbower at the moment. In case there\nare far-visioned leaders all Is well.\nIn case the perspective of statesmen\nis circumscribed by prejudices which\nrun rampant through the entire Eu\nropean fabric, then all is not well.\nEach political leader is governed by\nold tenets of party. Should he con\ntrol governments there always must\nhe adjustment of party creed with\nnational necessity. Oftentimes it is\ndone -without hindrance to pressing\nproblems. More often, however, the\npsychological moment for action and\ncomplete fruition of proposals is lost\nin the maze of expedient procrasti\nnation.\nPoliticians u\u00abt in Work.\nGen. Dawes\u2019 financial experts start\nwith a rush. They overrode, rough\nshod, many of the first puny ob\nstacles placed in their way. But dur\ning the time of their consideration of\nthe far-reaching questions involved\nIn the general problem of establish\ning Germany\u2019s ability to pay and\nmethods by which, she may do so the\nboll-weevils of Europea.n politics\nhave been permitted to get in their\nAt ,h<> Present juncture it\nT,. n b 1 a P pear that u wi h, -June or\nanything tangible comes\nork financial commission\u2019s\nNaturally, during the past two\nweeks with a mountain-high slack\nveer. 8 nd flK ,ros before them the\nxperts have found it difficult to\nuuare these with necessities of the\n\u2022\u2022ccasaion. Work as a result has been\nMowed up. but it generally has been\n.oneederi that this Will be completed\nbefore another fortnight has rolled\nno \"ll v .'-r- delays have fattened\nne appotitics ot those who would\npress, for consideration and adop\ntion. correllaries to the main prob\nlems\u2014side issues which may haz\nsird final consideration and adoption.\nI hough it was first announced that\nthe commission\u2019s findings would be\nadopted by all the allied countries in\ninto, it nevertheless has developed\n'mi* i? 10 rx P erts believe their report\nwill be riddled and to it attached\nmany amendments, just as the most\nefficient and fleetest of ocean liners\ncollect myriads of barnacles.\nPncls With loopholes.\nAny tentative European agreement\nframed to meet exigencies of any\nsituation, perforce by habit, must\nbe proporely amended, properly di- i\nRested and made to carry in some i\nsmall phase the view point of con-\nfiicting political elements in all the\npowers signatory to it. As a conse- 1\nquence. as in the case of the treaty i\nof Versailles, oftentimes the pacts I\n-ire so loosely worded as to permit;\n\u2022varying interpretations in various\ncountries. When an agreement or pact\nis signed without sonte clause or\nclauses permitting governmental in\nterpretation in face of dozens of\npossible, or impossible contingencies,\nihcn it is not considered a good\ndocument. While European nations in\ndealings among themselves like to\ndeliberate, ponder, then with flourish\n\u2022\u25a0f trumpets sign on the dotted line,\nit is quite the thing in governmental\ncircles to practice ingenuity in find\ning loopholes in previously loudly\nhailed agreements. It\u2019s all a part of\nEuropean statescraft and Gen. Dawes.\nknowing this, likewise knew that if\nhe was to achieve all that he set out\nto achieve, first he must Hen and\n-Maria\u201d his way through obstructions\nin the hope that his determination\nwould carry solution of the whole\nproblem Into the realms of safety and\n*way from the political bean shooters\nnaturally clustered about the sessions\n*>f the financial experts.\nMisgiving Is flrvi-alol.\nOn the very eve of a report from I\nthe financial experts, when it would\nppe-ar that but little stands in the I\n\u25a0way of adoption of the major features\nIndia Should Stay in Empire,\nBut Have Home Rule\u2014Gandhi\n(Continued from First Page.)\nhare ventured to place before India\nthe ancient law of self-sacrifice\u2014the\nobedience to the strength of the\nspirit.\n\u2018\"By non-violence 1 do> not mean\ncowardice. I do believe that where\nthere is only a choice between cow\nardice and violence I would advise\nidle nee. But I believe that forgive\nness adorns a-soldier. And so T am\nnot pleading- for India to practice\nnon-violence because she is weak, but\nbecause she is conscious of her power\nand strength. The ilishis, who dis\ncovered the law of non-violence, were\ngreater geniuses than Newton. Hav\ning- themselves known the use of\narras, they realized their' uselessness\nand taught a weary world that its\nsalvation lay not through violence,\nbut through non-violence.\n\u2018Therefore.\u201d the mahatma con\ncluded, \"I respectfully invite Amer\nicans to study carefully the Indian\nnational movement and they will\ni herein find an effective substitute\nfor war.\u201d\nBefore his imprisonment Mr. Gan\ndhi was a most severe critic of mod\nern civilization, and I asked if his\nviews had suffered any change.\n\u2018\u2018They remain unchanged.\" was\nhis quiet answer. \u2018\u2018My opinion of\nmodern civilization is that it is a\nworship of materialism, resulting in\nihe exploitation of the weak by the\nStrong. American wealth has be\ncome the standard. The United\nStates is the envy of all the other\nnations. Meanwhile moral growth\nhas become stunted and progress\nmeasured in pounds, shillings and\npence.\nHomeland of God*.\n\u201cThis land of ours, wc are told,\nwas once the abode of the gods. But\nii is not possible to conceive of gods\ninhabiting a land which Is made\nhideous by the smoke and din of mill\nchimneys and factories, and whose\nof the financier\u2019s program-\u2014one de\nsigned to hasten the day of settled\norder in Europe\u2014Paris. London and\nBerlin are filled w ith outcroppings of\nmisgiving. The French suspect the\nGermans and believe that Germany\nnever will consent to the proposals\ndeemed essential to eventual payment\nof reparations. Likewise the French\nare continuing their insistence that\nthe French and Belgian troops re\nmain in the Uuhr and Rhineland un\ntil Germany has paid, a highly dan\ngerous proceeding if equanimity be\nmaintained in the occupied regions\nduring the period of payment. The\natmosphere is filled with hypothetical\nconjecturing all designed to create\nan era of skepticism about the lime\nthe report of the committee will be\nhanded over to the reparations com\nmission for final action. Though\nmany attempts have been made to in\nfluence the financial experts and many\nof these have failed, it is expected\nthat the politicians of various coun\ntries will center their \u201cBig Berthas\"\nupon the reparations commission and.\nif failing to gain desired ends there,\nwill appeal to respective govern\nments.\nHard Doth Mill Kemain.\nIt is a question whether or not in\nthe\u2019 final analysis individual politi\ncians and groups of politicians will\ndare stand in the way of a concerted\ndemand of the people that there be\nquick and early settlement of vexa\ntious problems. However, there ere\nmany weeks yet to elapse before any\nsettlement can fie reached, and. in\nthe meantime, when the findings of\nthe experts become known, they will\nbe subject of vigorous propaganda\nfor and against in various countries\nof Europe. How well this will suc\nceed remains for time to solve, but it\nmust be taken for granted tli it Hie\nagreement is imperiled during the pe\nriod of procrastination.\nElections will be held in both\nFrance and Germany during early\nMay and it cannot be expected that\neither Foincare or the present Ger\nman regime will take serious chances\nof repudiation until it has been defi\nnitely determined whether they or\nsympathetic groups are to obtain fur\nther tenure of position.\nEven should Germany consent to\nall of the directions of the financial\nexperts and the reparations commis\nsion. there is doubt that France\nwould permit adoption until after the\nFrench elections. And it is hardly\nto be expected that the present Ger\nman government will sign any agree\nment that might create political cap\nital for the enemy with possible loss\nof elections.\nNationalist* \\re Feared.\nThe present government in Ger\nmany. though a coalition affair, nev\nertheless is dominated by leaders\ninimical to the cause of the mon\narchist nationalists, who have seized\nupon every pretext in recent years\nto further their cause in Germany.\nFurther capitulation to the allies,\nthough such capitulation means the\nrestoration of Germanic industrial\nand financial power, peace and order,\nwould be but ammunition in na\ntionalist hands and the cause of\ndemocratic government in Germany\nw ould be set back for a decade.\nThis contingency is not desired by\nthe socialists and more liberal ele\nments. As a consequence, anv a-tion\non the part of the Berlin regime has\nbeen the subject of close scrutiny at all\ntimes in order that the nationalist\nattacks may be checketi in the horn\ning.\nThe campaign between the various\nGerman parties evidentlv is to be a\nbitter one. The whole nation is\nspilt into many political groups, but\nthe nationalists and communists are\ndeclared to be the two strongest\ncamps at the moment, each bent\nupon wooing support from the mod\nerates, the conservative socialist and\ncatholic elements. It is believed the\nnationalists will put up a terrific\nfight for control of the next reichs\ntag or a predominant section of it,\nin order that the nationalist view-i\npoint always must be consulted This\nis not desired by either the\u2019 con\nnervatites or radical socialists for\nthe reason that in nationalist control\nalready is suspected attempted re\nturn to that old order which led to\nGermany\u2019s catastrophic position\nNeedless to say. should the Dawes\nfinancial plan bo adorned now and\nthe nationalists with their far-flung\npledges of resistance to the allies\nain control, then it would rot be\nvrorth the paper it is printed upon.\nOwing to pending elections. Eu\nrope sees necessity of the\nshunted aside for political xpedD\neney. and as long as such a slate of\naffairs is permitted to exist, condi\ntions in Europe never will improve\nfri C K P t F throU h lon Offering TnJ\ntribulation. economically, aociallv\nand financially. socially\nroadways are traversed by rushing\nengines, dragging cars crowded with\nmen who know not for the most pan\nwhat they arc after, do not care, and\nwhose tempers do not improve by be\ning uncomfortably packed together\nlike sardines in boxes. Factories\nhave risen on the corpses of men.\nwomen and children to create what\nwe call civilization.\u201d\nhen asked for his opinion on the\naction of the Supreme Court in bar\nring Indians from United States cit\nizenship. Mr. Gandhi replied that he\ndeplored the decision, and considered\nit due to American ignorance of\nIndia's civilization and its possibili\nties.\nFinally, when reminded of the fact\nthat all India worshiped him as a\n\u201csaint.\" that thousands of children\nwere being named \u201cGandhidas,\u201d that\nwreaths were daily freshened over\nhis picture In millions of homes\nthroughout India, Mr. Gandhi re\nplied simply:\n\u201cI think that word \u2018saint\u2019 should\nbe ruled out of present life. It is too\nsacred a word to be lightly applied\nto anybody, much less to one like\nmyself, who claims only to be ;l\nhumble searcher after truth.\u201d\nSuburban Telephone\nRates Are Criticized\nTo the Bdifor of The Star.\nCan any of your readers write and\npublish the reason the telephone\ncompany Is allowed to charge from\n5 to 25 cents for calls within four\nmiles, such as Clarendon, Va.\nAll the large cities I am acquainted\nwith include a radias of eight to\ntwelve miles in the regular service,\nwithout extra charge.\nThe telephone company, especially\nthe north exchange, charges up time\nIron! the moment they receive the\ntall until they happen to come in on\nthe line, regardless of when the sub\nscriber actually gets the party\nwantedi\nWhy should Washington people pay\nextra for calls on points a.s near as\nClarendon? New York. Philadelphia,\nPittsburgh and many other cities\nhave much better service in this re\nspect than Washington.\nC. H. UPWARDS.\nTHE SUNDAY STAR, WASHINGTON, H C MARCH 23, 1924\u2014PART 2.\ni'-\nReal Workers in the National Capital\nHY HERBERT COREY.\ni' M I ALLY one good deed for the rum-\nI runners. Not a voluntary\u2019 good\nJ[ dried, true. They do not acquire\nmerit by it. But it is a good\ndead for all that. Because of their illicit\nj activities the coast guard\u2014tho oldest,\nj proudest, most spotless service of the\nj United \u201cales government\u2014is to lx\nj doubled in size.\n\u2019\u2019Lord knows we\u2019ve wanted these boats\n1 long enough.\u201d the coast guardsmen say.\nThe rum-runners may blame them\nselves. They got too cocl\u00bbv. They have\nj been snooping in cargoes under the\nj eyes of helpless officers of the law,\n1 mounted on antiquated old wash tub;\nj that wallowed sidewise like crippled\ncrabs. They permitted themselves ges\nlures of derision. bought and paid\nj for some of the prohibition enforcement\n(officers, so that they might land whisky\n\u25a0where they pleased. The matter became\ni a national scandal.\nj International syndicates went into the\nrununing business, confident that Uncle\nj Sam would do nothing to hinder them.\nFrom twenty to fifty vessels are forever\nat anchor just outside New York, beyond\nj tin? twelve-mile limit. Fifty-six new\nj boats have been added in the past few\nmonths. The government of Grand\ni Bahama built bonded warehouses to ac\ncommodate tile whisky smugglers. St.\ni Fierro. Miquelon, has become the most\nI prosperous colony of France.\n\u201cWhat are we going to do about it?\"\nasked the officers of the prohibition unit.\nWell, there were two obvious things\njto do. The first was to throw a monkey\nI wrench in the gears of that rum fleet.\nThe second was to stop whisky peddling\niop shore. The anti-rum unit undertook\nto head off the blockade runners at\nsea without much success. They did\nj catch a boat now and then, but a fasi\nI launch is paid for by the profits of two\njor three successful voyages. The court\ni dockets arc so crowded with rum cases\nj that blockade runners hardly come to\ntrial.\nj \"They just walk in. thrown down a\n1 hundred-doliar bill for bail, and forget\nI about it.\" a court official told me the\ni other day.\nI\nReinforcement* for C\u00bbnM Guard.\ni Evidently rumming could not be stop-\nI ped while that fleet was in being. But\nmaritime activities are no part of the\nprohibition unit\u2019s duties, strictly speak\niug. Its job is ashore. The cnforc-e\n--i ment of the customs laws is one of the\nI thirteen major purposes the coast guard\nis presumed to have, but it was helpless.\nIts ships were too slow to catch a rum\nj m<T. The bottle fishermen could run\n.circles around its cutters. Further, its\nprincipal duty is to save life at sea.\nInterposition between the bottle and\n!an unhallowed thirst comes away\ni down in the list.\nj Therefore Congress is now eon\nsidering the Winslow bill, by the\nterms of which twenty destroyers\nI will be untied from the Navy docks\nj at which they are now rusting and\nj turned over to the coast guard.\nThat means that the guard can go\ni out to sea and sit down with the\nfleet. When it sees something it\nj does not like it can take steps to\nj have that particular thing changed.\nThe- chances are the price of scotch\nwill go up. In addition to the dc\nstroyers fifty or so fast launches' will\n!he turned over to the coast guard.\nI Then the slippy little boats that scoot\ni out to the rum fleet under cover of\nnight may find themselves blocked\nj off. The traffic between enforce\nment officers and the runners will be\nended.\n\"It is the pride of the coast guard\nThe Story the Week Has Told\nBV IfKVRV V BI\nThe following is a brief summary\nof the most important news of the\nworld for the seven days ended\nMarch 22:\n'Hie British Commonwealth of Na\ntions\u2014On March 18 it was announced\nto parliament that the government\nhad decided to chuck the project of\na naval base at Singapore. The house\nof lords at once passed a resolution\ndeploring the, decision. The matter\nis to be debated at length in the\ncommons. Defending the decision\nMr. MacDonald told the commons\nthat prosecution pf the Singapore\nproject would maim that interna\ntional good feeling and confidence\nwhich it was the prime aim of his\ngovernment\u2019s foreign policy to pro\nmote. His government proposed, he\nsaid, to maintain only a \u201cnucleus\" of\ndefenses and armaments and to place\nits chief reliance for security on\n\"good will, steps toward disarma\nment.\u201d that sort of thing.\nliieut. Col. Amory. first lord of the\nadmiralty in the late conservative\ngovernment, replied. He begged the\ngovernment to reconsider. Noble ges\ntures could not be relied on to pro\ncure peace and good will. In the re\ncent war Britain had suffered terri\nbly from unpreparedness due to the\nexcess of \"confidence.\u201d Since the\nwar the defenses of the empire had\ndangerously been reduced. As for the\ndanger of hurting foreign suscepti\nbilities, were not the susceptibilities\nof the dominions equally to be con\nsidered? The labor government was.\nindeed, repudiating imperial co-op\noration. He ended by observing that\nthe conservatives, on returning to\npower, would at once resume that\npolicy of imperial defense agreed on\nat the recent imperial conference of\npremiers, a policy of which the most\nimportant feature was the project of\na great naval base at Singapore.\nThe latter government could hardly\nhave decided otherwise. In view of\ncertain oft-repeated declarations of\nthe labor party, decision to proceed\nwith the Singapore, project would\nhave amounted to self-stultification\nand would probably have given mor\ntal offense to the superpac'flsts of the\nparty. But the decision taken has\naroused dangerous distrust and an\ntagonism among the conservatives\nand in Australia and New Zealand.\nThe British are going to hold naval\nmaneuvers in the vicinity of the\nBalearic Islands. As these islands\ncould furnish deadly bases against\nsurface vessels plying between the\nMediterranean ports of France and\nFrench Africa, the French are sus\npicious. They fear, or profess to\nfear, an alignment of Britain, Spain\nand Italy against France.\nThe Prince of Wales came another\ncropper the other day in a steeple\nchase\u2014one of the best sports and\nperhaps the worst horseman in- the\nworld.\nA curious situation has developed in\nthe Irish Free State, Minister of De\nfense Mulcahy and the army council\nhad been making a vigorous effort to\nrun down the principals in the recent\narmy mutineers. But the executive\ncouncil of the government (of which\nMulcahy was a member) conferred\nspecial full powers to deal with mat\nters relating to the mutinies on the\neommander-in-chlef of the army,\nGen. O'Duffy, and\u2014through Mr. O'Hig\ngin*. the minister of home affairs\u2014\npromised friends of the chief mull\nREAR ADMIRAL F. t. RILLARD.\nservice,\" Fays Rear Admiral F. C.\nBillard. captain-commandant, \u201cthat\nits honor has never been smirched.\nNo man of the service has ever been\nbought. Tlie record doesn\u2019t show I\nthat any has ever been scared.\"\nThe reason why the coast guard\nhas not been as active as might\nbe desired in blockading the rummers\nis two-fold. In the first place, its 1\nfirst and most important duty is to\nsave life and property. Its twenty\nsea-going ships are scattered along\nboth our shore lines. The motto of j\nthe service is \u201cAlways ready.\u201d A I\ncutter may reach port after a cruise\nto find orders awaiting is. It turns i\nabout and steams out to sea. Its I\ncoal bunkers are built high and wide I\nto provide for precisely that sort of\na call. Plenty of food and water is\nalways* in store.\n\u201cIf the emergency is an immediate i\none, a coast guard ship is expected\nto get under way in twenty minutes,\"\nsaJd Admiral Hillard. \u201cSteam is al- i\nways kept up. If the captain has j\ngone home to see his family and can- i\nnot get back in time the first officer;\ntakes the ship.\"\nDuties Numerous and Dangerous.\nin the ice season the coast guard i\ncutters patrol the berg lanes, f\u2019oast\nguardsmen marry and bury and hang\nand feed the the Alaskan Indians.\nThe proposed round-the-world flight\nwould not have been possible except 1\nthat the coast guard records die-\nplayed the only places on the Alcu-\ntian Islands where the Army fliers i\nneers that the government action\nanent the latter would be conciliato\nry. One wonders why Gen. Mulcaiiy\ndid not upon these proceedings resign\nincontinently; construing them as he\ndid. as personally belittling to him,\nas derogatory to his office, and as\nreversing, with probability of con\nsequences fatal to the state, his\npolicy of stern dealings with trea\nson. He did not resign, but ordered\na raid on a certain hostelry in Dub\nlin. where he hoped to bag the two\nchief mutineers'. Hen. Tobin and Col.\nDalton. These gentlemen were not\npresent, hut several other guilty\nofficers of lower rank were captured.\nC*n learning of the raid, the executive\ncouncil issued a public statement de\nnouncing it. whereupon MulcaUy ie\nsigned. declaring that the raid was\nordered under the provisions of the\ndefense forces act, which the govern\nment had no right to override or sus\npend.\nFrom the meager dispatches it\nwould seem that Gen. Mulcahy\u2019s\ncourse was indefensible, however\nmuch one may sympathize with his\nattitude toward treas >n.\nThe general demands a thorough\ninvestigation and airing of the whole\naffair, intimating that he has a good\ndeal to tell about \"brotherhoods and\nsecret societies\" and other curious\nthings in the army.\nOn the evening of March -1 a de\ntachment of British soldiers had just\ndisembarked on a pier at Queens\ntown. Ireland, when a motor car con\ntaining four men in the uniform of\nFree State army officers dashed up\nand haled on the beach nearby. The\noccupants whipped out a machine gun\nand fired on the Britons, killing one\nand wounding twenty-eight, of whom\nfour are likely to die. The car then\ndashed away. The heroes of the\ngallant feat are supposed to have\nbeen fanatical mutineers. Gen. Mul\ncahy may well cite this incident as\nvindicating his uncompromising at\ntitude toward fanatcal disaffection in\nthe army.\nThe mutineer-deserters have ac\ncepted the government\u2019s terms, which\ninvolve their surrender and release\non parole. Certainly all is not well\nwith the Free State. The Indian leg\nislative assembly at Delhi continues\nto reject government bills.\n4=\nItaly.\u2014-On March 1G Fiume was\nformally tyinexed to Italy. King Vic\ntor visiting the city to preside over\nthe ceremony, and add the crowning\ntouch, so to speak, to the festivities.\nD\u2019Annunzio was not there, and this\nfor sundry reasons was well; but the\nking did the handsome thing by cre\nating him, simultaneously with the\nformal annexation, prince of Monte\nNevoso, \u201cSnowy mountain,\u2019\u2019 on the\nJugoslav border, standing guard, one\nmight say, over Fiume.\n\nThe Caliphate.\u2014A dispatch from\nJerusalem states that King Hussein\nof the Hcjaz has assumed the title of\ncaliph and is about to summon a\npan-Islamic conference to discuss\nmatters of general interest to the\nworld of Islam.\nIf the. report is correct, it may be\ndoubted whether Hussein has acted\nwisely. Had he been content modesty\nto submit to a pan-Islamic congress\nhis claims to the Caliphate of Islam\nin competition with other claimants,\n,e might reasonably have counted on\nI victory, for no other claimant could\npresent so many of those qualifica\ncould land for gas and rest. Coast\nguard cutters save slvips at sea and\ndestroy derelicts and swatter into the\nbreakers to tow out stranded ships.\nI H is a hard service. No weather is\ntoo rough, no wave too high, to hold\nj them back. No job is too big for\nthe coast guardsmen to tackle.\nBut because of the character of the\nservice the cutters have been round\nbuttocked. strong, sturdy little ships,\nI designed to stay at sea in all weather,\nrather than to chase speed boats\nladen with rum. And their service\nto the merchant marine cannot be\ndiscontinued merely because of the\nj thirst ashore. Under a law now\nalmost 100 years old, they cruise\nthe seas from the beginning to the\nend of the winter season in search\nof mariners needing aid. In one\naverage year the lives of more than\n1 2.000 persons were saved. No evi\ndence is recorded under this head\nunless the individual would in all\nprobability have lost his life. Mil\ni lions of dollars in property are saved\nj each season.\nIf Congress grants the transfer of\nthe fast destroyers from the Navy\nj the coast guard will be able to con-\nI tinue its primary duty and still en\nforce the customs laws, for it will\n1 then have the tools with which to\nI work. Only one thing bothers Admiral\n1 Billard. The doubling of the facili\nties of the coast guard will entail\na doubling of the personnel. Officers\nand men of the coast guard have\nalways been hand-picked. They must\ntions which have been considered de\nsirable. if not essential, for the office.\nFor he is of the Koreish or tribe of\nthe prophet, he Is an independent rul\ner. and lie is in possession of the holi\nest places of Islam\u2014Mecca and Me\ndina. But by his fait accompli he\nmay fatally have antagonized the\nrest of Islam, and created another\nschism.\nAt any rate there is again an Arab\ncaliph, of sorts, for the first time\nsince IBIT. It should be remarked that\nin the history of Islam a plurality of\ncaliphs has been the rule rather than\nthe exception, and this too in the\ngreat days. Obviously a supreme\nCaliphate is not necessary to the\nspiritual health of Islam. An ele\nment of \u201cbunk\" was infused into the\ncaliphate question by that prime\nscoundrel. Abdul Hamid, in further\nance of his political pan-Islamic pro\ngram.\nChina\u2014Relations between Peking\nand Moscow are exceedingly strained,\nthe Chinese government having re\nfused to ratify an agreement between\nthe two govrnnients signed by Dr.\nWang, its representative; an agree\nment intended to be preliminary to\na definitive treaty and to form the\nbasis thereof. The Chinese govern\nment was particularly dissatisfied\nwitli clauses of the agreement relat\ning to Mongolia; from which coun\ntry the Chinese insist, and quite\nproperly, that the Russians remove\nthemselves. The Russian envoy hav\ning behaved with characteristic\nmuscovite insolence, the Chinese\ngovernment ordered him to leave\nPeking.\n-4=\nlulled Staten of America\u2014On\nMarch 18, the House passed the bonus\nbill, 05.5 to 54. The nomination of\nJustice Wilbur of California to be\nSecretary of the Navy has been con\nfirmed.\nThe four \"Douglas world cruisers.\u201d\nwith eight Army flyers aboard, left\nSanta Monica, Calif., for Seattle, on\nMarch IT. They are now fitting pon\ntoons at Seattle, whence they hop off\non April 1.\nOn March 20 Charles William Eliot,\npresident-emeritus of Harvard\\ was\nninety years old. The whole world\nsent congratulations and the Harvard\nauthorities announced gifts to the\nuniversity totaling $1,250,000 in honor\nof the occasion. The magnificent old\nman spoke for half an hour at a\nmeeting in Sanders Theater, which\ni meeting was attended by Chief Jus\ntice Taft as the representative of\nPresident Coolldge, and later he\nspoke for another half hour to the\nundergraduates assembled in Harvard\nyard. All will agree with Justice\nTaft\u2019s statement, that \u201che lias wield\ned greater power with the intelligent\ndemocracy of his country than any\nother unofficial citizen of his time.\u201d\n\nMiscellaneous\u2014On March 14 the\nleague of nations council did a record\nday\u2019s work. In addition to other\nmatters, it heard and approved the\nreport embodying proposals for a\nsettlement of the Memel question,\nsubmitted by the commission ap\npointed by itself, and by Mr.\n.Norman 11. Davis; it persuaded\nrepresentatives of Germany and\nPoland to accept, on behalf of their\nrespective governments, arbitration\nmeasure up to an exacting: standard\nin mind and strength and courage\nand devotion to duty.\n\u201cIt may seem a hard job to get\nthe right men.\" said Admiral Billard,\n\"but we do not worry. We\u2019ll get\nthem. The wrong sort of a man could\nnot stay in the service.\"\nThat\u2019s where tradition counts. The\ncoast guard is the oldest maritime\nservice in the United States gov. rn\nraent. Born in 1790, it antedated the\nNavy by some years. It began with\nten cutters, carrying two officers and\nsix men each. The duty then was\nto watch smuggling in the ports and\nenforce the maritime laws. Then\nthe spread of piracy demanded larger\nvessels. The coast guard has taken\npart in every war of United\nStates except that, against Tripoli.\nIt fought and captured French and\nBritish privateers in the early years\nand German submarines in the great\nwar.\nNo Bribery or DiahonnMy.\n\u201cWithout a blot, mind you,\" says\nthe captain-commandant. \u201cNot one\nman of our service has ever been\ncharged w\u2019ith taking a b\u2019 ho or dis\nhonesty. Little things, yes. They're\nhusky, full-bodied men in the coast\nguard. They have to to stick to\nthe work. But no big things. The\nService is clean.\"\nThirty years ago he gave up teach\ning Latin and Greek to the sprout\ning youth to enter the service. It\nijeemed an odd start.\n\"I don\u2019t know w-hy,\u201d he said. \u201cNot\nthe love for adventure, particularly.\nI wanted to serve the government at\nsea, I think.\u201d\nSo he has been with the coast guard\never since. Not long ago an effort\nwas made to merge the coast guard\nwith the Navy. That was defeated.\nThe coast guard service is entirely\ndistinct and naval officers are not\npermitted to enforce civilian laws.\nMilitarism lies that way. But the\ncoast guardsmen had not been fairly\ntreated in the matter of pay or rank\nor retirement until a recently en\nacted law placed officers and men on\na parity with the Navy in all these\nmatters. Now the guard is to be still\nfurther increased, so that it can per\nform its manifold duties to its own\nsatisfaction.\nSpent Slurry Tear* at Sea.\nSixteen of Admiral Billard's thirty\nyears\u2019 service were spent at sea. Then\nthat long-buried pedagogic instinct\nmanifested itself and he was placed\nin charge of the coast guard serv\nice\u2019s own academy, at New London.\nThere its priced material is made\nready for any one of the varied serv\nices the coast guard demands of its\nmen. Its officers must know how\nto board a wallowing ship at sea or\nrun a life boat through the surf.\nThey must have a bookful of laws at\ntheir fingers' ends; be able to lay a\nfive-inch gun or navigate a dismasted\nhooker by dead reckoning, or reduce\na mutinous crew* to order by a blink\nof the eye.\n\u201cAnd they can,\u201d says Admiral Bil\nlard. He\u2019s the proudest man in the\nservice of the United States. He\nknows the coast guard will measure\nup to any job that is given it. He\nknows that when a coast guardsman\nis toid to do he does not come back\nwith an alibi. There is a book tilled\nwith the names of officers and men\nwho have been commended for heroic\nconduct. \"The others,\" says Billard.\n\u201chaven't had their chance.\"\nof the vexed question of German\nminorities in Poland; it cleaned up\npreliminaries relating to the league\nproject for Hungary\u2019s rehabilitation,\nand it made an appropriation for re\nlief of the starving Albanians,\nInformation is lacking as to the\ndetails of the Memel report, but it is\nsaid to be extremely unsatisfactory\nto Warsaw, which may refuse to ac\ncept its recommendations.\nThe French senate lias passed\nPoincare\u2019s financial and decretorv\nmeasures, and presuniablv thev are\nnow law.\nThey are rowing it again in\nPortugal\u2014 every body on strike. No\nchance for Portugal, apparently, short\nof another Suevic invasion.\nit looks as though Shah Ahmad\nMirza of Persia is going to be tired\nand there is going to be a republic\nof Persia. There are republics and\nrepublics. One wonders whether the\nbenevolent Chicherin has his finger\nin this pie.\nCorrects Errors.\nCorrespondent Says Writers Err\non Historical Facts.\nTo the Editor of The Star;\nI recently took occasion to call at\ntention to errors made by two of\nyour special writers in statements of\na historical character. Since that\ntime I have been forced to add three\nmore to the list of the names of\nwriters of national repute who handle\nsome facts in our country\u2019s history\ncarelessly.\nReferring to the non-election of a\nPresident by the electoral college, and\nthus sending the matter to the Con\ngress for determination both Mr.\nWile and Mr. Lawrence have recently\nstated that such a thing had occurred\nbut once (Mr. Wile twice, over the\nradio, and Mr. Lawrence in The\nStar). The truth is that twice has\nthe House of Representatives been\ncompelled to elect a President be\ncause of the failure of the electors\nto do so.\nIn the electoral college of 1800,\nThomas Jefferson and Aaron Burr\ntied for the presidency, whereupon\nthe House elected Mr. Jefferson.\nAfter the failure in 1824 of the\nelectors to settle the free-for-all con\ntest engaged in by Jackson. Adams,\nClay and Crawford, the House was\nagain called upon to act, with the\nresult that the Clay Congressmen\nvoted for Mr. Adams, who was elect\ned. President Adams then made Mr.\nClay Secretary of State. An appar\nent bargain-and-salc transaction of\nthis character would surely call for a\ncongressional investigation in this\nyear of grace.\nA few days ago Mr. Messenger in\nThe Star stated, speaking with ref\nerence to the likelihood of the coming\nelection, being sent to the Congress\nfor settlement. Jhat the republicans con\ntrolled a majority of the state dele\ngations in Congress. They do not.\nCounting Wisconsin, they have but\ntwenty-three states, while the dem\nocrats have twenty, with five states\ntied. Thus the republicans are two\nstates shy of a majority, with the\nprospect of this being reduced to one\nif the House unseats Mr. Bloom of\nNew York, thereby giving the re\npublicans oootrsl of that delegation.\nJ. JAQUES.\nHOUSE NOW TO WEIGH\nPRESIDENTIAL PROBLEM\nConstitutional Omissions in Regard to\nVacancies in Office Probably Will\nBe Supplied by Proposals.\nHI WILL P. KEXXEDY.\nPROPOSALS to supply very se\nrious omissions in the Con\nstitution which might leave\nthis government without a\nPresident or any clear direction as\nto how to proceed to fill the office\nof Chief Executive will be given care\nful consideration this week by the House\"\ncommittee on the election of Pres\nident, Vice President and representa\ntives in Congress, which has before\nIt the, Xorris resolution for a consti\ntutional amendment, which passed the\nSenate during the week.\nThe Xorris resolution proposes an\namendment to the Constitution so\nthat a newly elected Congress shall\ntake office the first Monday in Jan\nuary after its election and the Pres\nident and Vice President shall be\ninaugurated the third Monday in\nJanuary. A two-tbirds vote is re\nquired in the House as well as in\nthe Senate before this* proposed con\nstitutional amendment can be sub\nmitted to the states for ratification.\nAs the House committee already has\nreported favorably a joint resolution\nthat is substantially the same as the\nNorris amendment. Representative\nHays B. M hitc of Kansas, chairman\nof the House committee, is willing\nto move substitution of the Senate\nmeasure for the House measure to\nfacilitate its passage, and feels con\nfident that the two-thirds vote can\nbe had in the House.\nWould Care for Eventualities.\nBut Representative Whit\u00a9 is very\nanxious that if the Constitution is\namended in this respect the amend\nment should take care of any possi\nble eventuality and supply any long\nstanding omission. It has been\nbrought to his attention that:\n(a) Any new amendment to the\nConstitution ought to provide away\nto take care of the situation that\nmight arise if both the President\nelect and the Vice President-elect\nshould die between the time of their\nelection and the lime of their inaugu\nration. Attempts have been made in\nthe past to fill that omission in the\nConstitution, but nothing definite has\nbeen done.\nfb) There is a. possibilitv that in\nthe coming presidential election the\nchoice may be thrown into the House\nfor President and into the Senate for\nVice President. If both the House\nand Senate fail to make their choice\nbefore March 4. by interpretation the\npresidential succession act comes into\nplay. This provides that the Secre\ntary of State would then assume the\noffice of President and should\npromptly call a special session of\nCongress\u2014but for what purpose the\nlaw is silent\u2014presumably to see that\nthe will of the people is safeguarded\nagainst a hold-over cabinet officer\nfrom the previous repudiated admin\nistration.\nCoutUotioul Prarisi...\nThe Constitution provides for what\nshall be done \u2018\u2018in case of the re\nmoval, death, resignation or in\nability\u201d of the President. It has\nlong been a moot question as\nto when \u2018\u2018inability\u201d exists, and who\nshall determine whether a President\nis \u201cinable.\u201d This question was\nthrashed out during President Wil-\nI son\u2019s severe illness.\nWHAT IS SUCCESS?\nIV\u2014The Biggest Thing in the World\n(Continued from First Page.)\nperiod of activity prior the the war\nwhich was followed by the dullness\nof 1914. Next cam\u00a9 the war boom\nand the post-war boom, which were\nfollowed by the reaction of 1920.\nIn your mind's eye picture this chart\nreaching back into the days of the\nAmerican civil war, then backward,\nstill backward into the days of the\nRevolutionary war. Crossing to the\nold world as the scene of activities,\ncarry the chart still further back\nto the Biblical days, when the seven\nfat years followed the seven lean\nyears.\nHere is a simple illustration of\nwhat the law of action and reaction\nmeans to every reader. The following\nletter was written by a young man\nin New York city to bis folks in\nMaine. It was dated January. 190 S,\nduring the business depression:\n\"Dear Mother: 1 haven't entirely lost\nheart\u2014l won't ever do that\u2014but there\nseems mighty little chance of my\nmaking a success here. 1 am work\ning: harder than I ever did in my life\n\u2014trying to get work. I have an\nswered every advertisement in every\npaper. 1 have called on everybody\nthe census-taker called on, and also\na few more that I bet he missed. I\nguess I'm no good. But cheer up, one\nman told me today he would put my\nname on file, whatever that means.\n\u25a0\u2018Write often.\n\u201cWith lots of love to everybodv.\n\u201cAUSC.\u201d\nThat letter may sound familiar to\nsome mothers and fathers. Perhaps\nyou have had such letters from your\nown sons. You can read between the\nlines, and you know what that boy\nwas up against. You can see him,\ncan\u2019t you. worn down by the toughest\njob in the world \u2014which is hunting a\njob\u2014footsore, heartsick, about down\nand out. but still putting on a cheer\nful face so as not to worry the folks.\nPreventing Hanna Heartbreaks.\nWhat would it have meant to this\nboy if his mother could have written\nto him the real facts? Suppose she\nhad pointed out to him that the rea\nson work was so hard to find was\nnot because he was \u201cno good.\u201d not\nbecause the country had gone to the\ndogs, not because a young man had\nno chance to succeed, not because\nthere was no room at the bottom\nbut just because of a temporary\nmovement of this fundamental law.\nThen she could have explained that if\nhe would de patient the working so\nthe law would later help him as it\nthus handicapped him.\nThe man who wrote this letter has\ntoday a wife and family and a good\nbusiness. Today he is looked upon as\nsuccessful. But he said as he ex\nhibited this letter which his mother\nhad saved: \"It makes me smile a lit\ntle now. but I hope never to come\nnearer death than when I sat down\nthat night to write home! I can't\nhelp thinking what a lot of real suf\nfering in this world would be saved\nIf people only understood the cause\nof It. if they only realized it was\nmerely a swing in business condi\ntions and would soon be over.\u201d\nTemptation of High Wages.\nHere is another letter that may in\nterest readers wfco like letters be\ncause they are real human documents\nand not the expression of dry theo\nries. This letter was written by a\nyoung lady:\n\"October 18. 1919.\n\"My Babson; Please don't\nthink I have not enjoyed my work\nwith the Babson Statistical Orgnni\nzation. It has been most congenial,\nand I hope I have been useful. I\nbave certainly, tried to be. My only\nThere was an old statute of ITS\",\nwhich was repealed at the lime the\npresidential succession act was\npassed, which provided that \u201cin the\ncase of removal, death, resignation\nor inability of both the President and\nVice President o i the X'nited Stale-,\nthe President of the Senate, or. if\nthere is none, then the Speaker of the\nHouse of Representatives, for th*\ntime being, shall act as President tin\ntil the disability is removed or a\npresident elected.\u201d That recognized\na possible vacancy in the office of Presi\ndent and provided for a temporary Pres\nident. The Constitution did not use\nthe word \u201cvacant,\u201d but the lav.\npassed within three years after the\nConstitution became operative, and lr\nth\u00a9 drafting of which those who had\nframed the Constitution took a prom\ninent part, went further and provided\nwhat should happen if the office\nshould \u201cbecome vacant.\u201d\nIf that old law was in force no\"\nit would care for the situation which\nsome close students of government\nforesee may arise in the next election\nThe Xorris amendment does not\ntake care of the situation growing\nout of the death of both the President\nand Vice President elect before then\ninauguration. which this old la\"\nwould have done.\nThe Xorris amendment cannot take\ncare of the situation that might arise\nin the next election if the House anil\nSenate should both fail to elect a\nPresident or Vice President before\nMarch 4. when President Coolidge's\npresent term expires-\u2014because there\nisn\u2019t time to have such Constitutional\namendment ratified by the states.\nWould Remedy Contingency.\nThe Xorris amendment seeks to\nremedy such a contingency for the\nfuture, however, by providing that\nCongress by law shall designate some\nofficer to act as President after the\nterm of the President expires until\nthe House shall elect a President or\nthe Senate elect a Vice President, ex\ntending the time for voting in Con\ngress from the third Monday in Jan\nuary, when the President would au\ntomatically go out of office, until\nMarch 4 at noon.\nIf the House should fail to elect\na President by noon on Mareh 4, th-\nXorris amendment provides that the\nVice President elected by the Senaf\nwould become President for the full\nterm. But if there he no Vice Presi\ndent the amendment might also he con\nstrued as meaning that the House would\ncontinue to try to elect a President after\nMarch 4. because it says that the officer\ni designated by Congress to act as Pre.-i\n--1 dent \"shall act accordingly until the\nI House of Representatives chooses\nI I\u2019resident, or until the Senate choose.-\na Vice President.\u201d\nThis might result in an interesting\nand spirited race between the House\nand Senate to see which could beat\nthe other to picking a President\nsince the Senate's choice for Vice\nPresident would then become Presi\ndent.\nThat would be some race, with the\ni House voting on three candidates and\nI the Senate voting on two.\nIt is proposed to correct the law\nnow so as to cover the situation that\ncould arise in the coming campaign,\nthe presidential succession law\u2014the\nby amending the presidential succession\nlaw\u2014under which as it now stands th\nsuccession might devolve upon the Sec\nretary of State, although that law do<\nnot in terms meet a contingency of ex\nactly this kind. The fear is, however,\nthat in this way a repudiated admin\nistration might be given a chance to\nperpetuate itself in office.\nreason for now sending you this let\nter resigning my position is because 1\nhave been offered a place in the\nCompany, and the} offer a very much\nlarger salary than 1 am getting her,\nPersonally, even the higher pav would\nnot influence me to make the chang.\nbut with others partly dependent\nupon my earnings I really feel this\nis a serious consideration.'\nt \u201cI shall always be greatly interest\ned in your work and that of the or\nganization, in which I leave man.'\nfriends. I thank you for all that you\nhave done for me.\n\"Sincerely yours,\nj Note that this letfVr is dated C>-\ntober. 1919. What was happening ii.\nOctober, 1919? Business was boom\ning. Everybody was employed. Every\nbody was getting big wages and\nsalaries. It was hard to get help\nBusiness organizations were scouting\naround trying to get each other\u2019.-;\nemployes, just as a certain compan>\nattracted this girl away from th<\nBabson offices. She was a valuabb\ngirl, and we should have liked to\nraise her pay and meet this other\noffer if we could have done so in\nfairness to the rest of the organiza\ntion. As this was impossible, the\nonly thing to do was to accept her\nresignation, at the same time strong\nly advising her against leaving. Th-.\nadvice, however, was not accepted.\nResults of Business Depression.\nWhat happened? For a month or\nso everything went merrily as a mar\nriage bell. Then, about the middle\nof 1920, the storm broke. Business\nbegan to slide down hill. Business\norganizations retrenched. Employes\nwere discharged right and left. The\nparticular company which had lured\naway the girl by the bait of a fancy\n1 salary turned right around and dis\ncharged her. She felt that she had\nfailed. She was completely dis\ncouraged.\nInstead of urging her to take the\nother job. as they did. her parents\nshould have explained to her this\nfundamental law. Any parents who\npermit their children to ouit a secut,\njob just on the brink of a business\ndepression not only deserves to lose\nsuch financial help as the children\nmay be contributing, but they de\nserve to lose also their children's\nconfidence and respect. Ambitions\nfor our feoys and girls arc justified.\nOs course.\" we want them to succeed.\nBut don't let love blind our eyes to\na fundamental law of success.\nI.aw That Make* or Breaks l'\u00bb.\nBet not our ambition for success be\na blind ambition. In times of de\npression teach confidence and hope,\ncourage and enterprise. But in times\nof great prosperity teach steadiness,\nprudence, caution. vigilance and\nservice.\nSome of the world's best and great\nest men have frankly said that much\nof their success they owe to, lessons\n'learned at their mother's knee and\nto the counsels of a wise father. Oh,\nif all those lessons and counsels\nmight include instruction about the\nfundamental law of action and reac\ntion! What a priceless legacy and in\nheritance it is for a boy and girl to\ngo into tlie world with a clear under\nstanding of how the world works,\nhow fundamental law operates, hon\nit makes us or breaks us according\nas we shape our course to profit bj\nits power or vainly try to stem its\noverwhelming tides. As Shakespeare\nsaid: \u201cThere is a tide in the affairs\nlof men which, taken at the flood,\nleads on to fortune.\" The time to\ncatch this tide is at the bottom of\ntho long swing upward.\n(Copyright. 1923, Fleming 11. Rovell Com\npany. First published in this newspaper by\narrangement with\nsac Park. Miss\n3","height":"25071","width":"19554"}}
